From an ordering standpoint, why is this done before all the brand/family/model parsing when handling of the potential stepping data is done later?  It reads a little funny in the diff.

I considered it to be the same as part of all of the initial strtok_r() calls, but it's failure isn't fatal. Also, we reuse last, after which we can't call strtok_r again.

Would it be clearer if I ended up moving the comment above the original group and then immediately did the stepping part?
Yeah, I think moving the comment down would make it a little clearer.
Maybe VERIFY() that we've not exceeded CPROC_MAX_STEPPINGS?
I've made this explicitly fail rather than just abort.

style nit: I'd think about doing two versions here, for nsteps == 0 and > 0, rather than having printf()s sprinkled with ternary checks everywhere.  Your call, but this seems a lot harder to grok as-is.
I've tried what you suggest, how do you feel about it now?

Do the parens balance out here? It looks like you output one open paren at line 926, another at line 944, then two close parens here, but then one more at line 966. Maybe I am not matching things up correctly?
